title: For Sale:  Surefire M900A weapon light
postcontent:
Alright, here’s the rundown on the light.  It has an incandescent bulb that advertises 120 lumens of white light output.  Don’t tell Obama about these bulbs.  My version has a quick release lever mount to attach to the bottom of a quad rail, making it very easy to take off and put back on.  I’m normally not much for quick release anything, but I like it in this case.  Tape switches are built into the sides of the vertical grip area, there is a permanent on/off switch on the bottom, and a little bitty tape switch at the top back of the unit for ‘navigation lights’.  I went a step further and added a blue light filter onto the head.  At first I just wanted it to protect the primary lense, then I found that blood will stand out in a dark area under blue light.  It hasn’t come in handy yet, but it could some day.  

I'm selling it only because I'm playing with other setups and don't use this one any longer.

title: For Sale:  JPSCS-10 JP Silent Captured Buffer / Spring for AR-10 type rifles SPRING BUFFER AR 10
postcontent:
This is barely used and still looks brand new. 

JP Custom Buffer Springs and Silent Captured Springs
The “spoon over a cheese grater” sound emitted by modern sporting rifles whenever they’re charged or fired has always been one of the AR platform’s ugly blemishes and one we’ve worked ardently to eliminate.  After years of specially selecting buffer tube manufacturers based on the quality of their tubes’ interior finish, we opted to design and produce our own action springs with a perfect centerless-ground and precision-polished outside diameter.  These JP Custom Buffer Springs are an inexpensive way to see exactly why we have a reputation for having the quietest, smoothest rifles on the market.

Our pursuit of perfection didn’t stop with springs though and led ultimately to the creation of the JPSCS™ Silent Captured Spring (patent pending), new for 2012. Maintaining all the benefits of our polished buffer springs and proprietary LMOS™ buffer, this combination buffer-spring assembly eliminates the friction of standard buffer components resulting in outstanding smoothness and sound abatement. What’s more, the spring is removable from the assembly for custom tuning, and both the AR-15 and AR-10 versions of the JP Silent Captured Springs are functional in rifle- and carbine-length operating systems. The AR-15 version fits and functions in any gas-operated AR-15 variant, regardless of caliber and the AR-10 version should fit and function in any large-frame AR-10-type platform. The JPSCS is not compatible with any 9mm AR variant or any blowback system using a solid (weighted) carrier.





Silent Captured Spring for AR-10-type rifles

Includes spacer to allow for installation in both carbine-length and rifle-length buffer tubes.

Compatibility
The JPSCS-AR10 is designed to work in standard 7-inch M16/M4-length buffer extension tubes on .308 AR-type rifles like the DPMS LR-308. Armalite .308 rifles likewise use these standard M16 extension tubes with rifle-length stocks, so the JPSCS-AR10 will function normally when installed with the supplied spacer. However, Armalite’s .308 carbines use a slightly longer, nonstandard carbine extension tube. The JPSCS-AR10 can still be used with these extension tubes by installing the spacer, which must be modified to fit. Alternately, the system will function readily if the longer Armalite carbine tube is replaced with a standard 7-inch .223 carbine extension tube.

The JPSCS-AR10 is not compatible with the Rock River Arms LAR-8 because of its longer bolt stroke and subsequently longer extension tube.

title: For Sale:  Beautiful Italian .44 Navy Black Powder Revolver
postcontent:
Well, I have wanted one of these since I was 14 years old and met an old,old gentleman on the edge of our neighborhood who grew up in Charlotte when it was all dirt roads and told us stories of his brother and him finding British coins when plowing where major roads are today (he has been dead along time now) told us the best they could figure it was probably stragglers fleeing from the beating they took at Kings Mountain and got picked off on the way through here but I guess the Brit soldiers weren't the only one's with British money back then but sure had us young boys  wound up all up and then all going into the woods for years digging for British treasures back in the 1970's ha ha

Yep, you can almost never get anything from me without a story so excuse me if you are a Type A and hate this stuff. My point was (which makes the pistol worth zero dollars more, but hell I like a good story ha ha)  one day after telling us about watching over World War 1 German prisoners when he was a young man (he said many were just farm boys just like him just doing what they were told to do and he said they were good ole boys). Anyhow after he had us all wide eyed with story after story he told us to wait a minute and one day came out of his house with an original black powder .44. I can't remember what style because I was too amazed at the "chain fire" stories he told us if you were under attack or careless and didn't prep the weapon correctly.

So today Charlie is long gone, his stories live on with me and the guys I grew up with that moved on to places unknown and over 35 years later I’ve got a wicked old .44 black powder.
I saved this one from a slob who had it I don't think ever cleaned or polished it. Fortunately it is an older reproduction and is well built and tight so it cleaned up pretty nice as I hope the pictures show.Even has a Naval Battle scene engraved in the cylinder (hard to see in pics but it is there for anyone drooling over it to see)

I know these aren't some super high dollar pistols but like the story I related, just having one displayed somewhere draws everyone's attention. The brass and wood is so "pretty" my wife was even giving it a "Wow, that came out niiiiice!" my son's were impressed with that but even more by the attention demanding .44 business end of the barrel and the dogs running and hiding when I slowly would click the hammer back into firing position (only time my dogs are smart ha ha). 

While it is older technology it is still an awesome .44 and will blow a home invader right back out the way they came in if they were stupid enough to "visit". Get an extra cylinder like Clint Eastwood did so famously in his movie and pull the cylinder release and slid in a preloaded cylinder and now you have a "speed loader" (well maybe "quicker" loader ha ha).
So as good of a story as it can be, and a chance to share our countries history with sons or Grand kids as they look at it in awe it still can serve as a very effective weapon if you need to call it back into service. SHOW AN GO!

I don't want to sell it straight out (unless you have to much money ha ha) but I would like to trade it for a more modern pistol or nice rifle. You know I like a good story and of course like cool or even wicked weapons. I reached my goal getting this one and got all of the oohs and ahhh's out of it since then so time for another new "toy"

If you respond please send pictures,model numbers and anything that goes with your trade (NOT the one's like "Hey I got me a camo sofa an uh .22" with zero details ha ha).

I am happy to keep it if needed but here she is if you want her worse than me. Is a damn nice and very cool piece. Thanks for enduring my stories if you made it here to the end.
